06628nam a22011775i 9780691205366DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20212021nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97806912053667 a10.1515/97806912053662doi  a(DE-B1597)567557  a(OCoLC)1201694155  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aJC585b.S756 2021eb 7aHIS0360002bisacsh04a320.01/1223  aMS 35302rvk0(DE-625)rvk/123683:1 aStovall, Tyler, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhite Freedom :bThe Racial History of an Idea /cTyler Stovall. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (440 p.) :b31 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Freedom and Its Dark Sides -- tPart 1 -- tChapter 1: Savage Freedom: Piracy, Childhood, and Alternate Racial Visions of Liberty -- tChapter 2: Lady of Freedom, Lady of Whiteness: The Statue of Liberty as Symbol of White Freedom -- tPart 2 -- tChapter 3: Black Slavery, White Freedom: Freedom and Race in the Era of Liberal Revolution -- tChapter 4: Empire, Racial Citizenship, and Liberal Democracy -- tPart 3 -- tChapter 5: Fighting for Whose Liberty? Freedom and Race in the Era of Total War -- tChapter 6: Freedom Now? The Fall and Rise of White Freedom during the Cold War -- tConclusion: White Freedom and Freedom from Whiteness -- tNotes -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe racist legacy behind the Western idea of freedomThe era of the Enlightenment, which gave rise to our modern conceptions of freedom and democracy, was also the height of the trans-Atlantic slave trade. America, a nation founded on the principle of liberty, is also a nation built on African slavery, Native American genocide, and systematic racial discrimination. White Freedom traces the complex relationship between freedom and race from the eighteenth century to today, revealing how being free has meant being white.Tyler Stovall explores the intertwined histories of racism and freedom in France and the United States, the two leading nations that have claimed liberty as the heart of their national identities. He explores how French and American thinkers defined freedom in racial terms and conceived of liberty as an aspect and privilege of whiteness. He discusses how the Statue of Liberty—a gift from France to the United States and perhaps the most famous symbol of freedom on Earth—promised both freedom and whiteness to European immigrants. Taking readers from the Age of Revolution to today, Stovall challenges the notion that racism is somehow a paradox or contradiction within the democratic tradition, demonstrating how white identity is intrinsic to Western ideas about liberty. Throughout the history of modern Western liberal democracy, freedom has long been white freedom.A major work of scholarship that is certain to draw a wide readership and transform contemporary debates, White Freedom provides vital new perspectives on the inherent racism behind our most cherished beliefs about freedom, liberty, and human rights.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aLiberty. 0aNation-state and globalization. 0aRacism. 0aWhite peoplexRace identity. 0aWhitesxRace identity. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh  aAmerican Revolution.  aBlack Lives Matter.  aCold War era.  aDavid Roediger.  aEllis Island.  aFrench Empire.  aHaitian slave revolt.  aJim Crow.  aMartin Luther King.  aNell Irvin Painter.  aRosa Parks.  aRough Crossings.  aSaint-Domingue.  aSeizing Freedom.  aSelma to Montgomery marches.  aSelma.  aSimon Schama.  aThe Hist